# Convert the training data to a time series object
# Frequency is set to 366 because 2020 is a leap year
yy <- ts(training_data, frequency = 366, start = c(2020, 22/366))
plot.ts(yy, main = "Original COVID-19 Cases in Colorado (22nd Jan - 31st Dec '20)")

print("The substantial increase in cases at the end of the year shows the virus had been spreading more quickly.")
## [1] "The substantial increase in cases at the end of the year shows the virus had been spreading more quickly."
## PART 1: auto.arima (p,d,q) x (P,D,Q) model  ##

# Fit Auto-ARIMA model
auto_arima <- auto.arima(yy)

# Print the results
print(auto_arima) # Auto-ARIMA results: (p,d,q) = (0,2,1)
## Series: yy 
## ARIMA(0,2,1) 
## 
## Coefficients:
##           ma1
##       -0.6271
## s.e.   0.0430
## 
## sigma^2 = 194073:  log likelihood = -2574.63
## AIC=5153.25   AICc=5153.29   BIC=5160.93
# Check for stationarity using Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test
adf_test_result <- adf.test(residuals(auto_arima))

# Print the test results
print(adf_test_result) # Estimated p = 0.09364 (< 0.10) => so yd is now stationary.
## 
##  Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test
## 
## data:  residuals(auto_arima)
## Dickey-Fuller = -3.1677, Lag order = 7, p-value = 0.09364
## alternative hypothesis: stationary
# Predict and forecast COVID cases for Jan 01 - Feb 10, 2021 using the Auto-Arima model 
auto_arima.predict <- forecast:::forecast.Arima(auto_arima, h = 41, level = c(68, 90))
plot(auto_arima.predict)

# Print the summary of the Auto-Arima model
summary(auto_arima)
## Series: yy 
## ARIMA(0,2,1)

## PART 2: Alternative ARIMA models and forecasts ##

# Initialize to store alternative models and their BICs
alternative_models <- list()
alternative_models_bic <- numeric()

# Iterate over possible values of p and q, fixing d to 2.
for(p in 0:2) {
    for(q in 0:3) {
        model <- arima(yy, order = c(p, 2, q))

        if (!is.null(model)) {
            model_name <- paste("ARIMA(", p, ",2,", q,")", sep = "")
            alternative_models[[model_name]] <- model
            alternative_models_bic[model_name] <- BIC(model)
            
            # Generate forecasts for each model
            forecast_values <- forecast:::forecast.Arima(model, h = 41, level = c(68, 90))
            
            # Plot the forecast
            cat("Forecast:",  model_name)
            plot(forecast_values)
        }
    }
}
## Forecast: ARIMA(0,2,0)

## Forecast: ARIMA(0,2,3)

## Forecast: ARIMA(1,2,0)

## Forecast: ARIMA(1,2,1)

## Forecast: ARIMA(1,2,2)

## Forecast: ARIMA(1,2,3)

## Forecast: ARIMA(2,2,0)

## Forecast: ARIMA(2,2,1)

## Forecast: ARIMA(2,2,2)

# Print the BIC for each model

## BIC for each model:
print(alternative_models_bic)

## PART 3, 4 & 5: Average forecast from the best and good models using BIC weights. ##

# Find the best model by the lowest BIC value
best_model_bic <- min(alternative_models_bic)
best_model_name <- names(which.min(alternative_models_bic))
best_model <- alternative_models[[best_model_name]]

# Print the name and BIC of the best model
cat("The best model is", best_model_name, "with a BIC of", best_model_bic, "\n")
## The best model is ARIMA(0,2,1) with a BIC of 5160.93
# Identify the models within the threshold of +/- 1 point from the best BIC
model_names <- names(which(abs(alternative_models_bic - best_model_bic) <= 1))

# Exclude the best model from the set of models
good_models <- model_names[model_names != best_model_name]

cat("# Set of good models within the vicinity of the best model:")
## # Set of good models within the vicinity of the best model:
good_models
## [1] "ARIMA(0,2,3)"
# BICs of the best/good models
set_of_models_bic <- alternative_models_bic[model_names]

# Compute the BIC weights for each model
bic_weights <- exp(-0.5 * (set_of_models_bic - best_model_bic))
bic_weights <- bic_weights / sum(bic_weights)

# Define the forecasts from the best model and good models
best_model_forecast <- forecast:::forecast.Arima(best_model, h = 41, level = c(68, 90))
good_model_forecasts <- lapply(good_models, function(model_name) {
  good_model <- alternative_models[[model_name]]
  forecast:::forecast.Arima(good_model, h = 41, level = c(68, 90))$mean
})

# Combine forecasts into a matrix
all_forecasts <- cbind(best_model_forecast$mean, do.call(cbind, good_model_forecasts))
colnames(all_forecasts) <- model_names 
print(all_forecasts)

# Calculate the weighted average forecast
weighted_average_forecast <- rowSums(all_forecasts * bic_weights[match(model_names, colnames(all_forecasts))])

# Print the weighted average forecast

## PART 6: Computing Mean Absolute Percentage Errors ##

# Calculate MAPE for the best model ARIMA(0,2,1)
mape_arima021 <- mean(abs(colorado_cases[346:386,'CO']$CO - best_model_forecast$mean) / colorado_cases[346:386,'CO']$CO) * 100

# Print MAPE for the best model ARIMA(0,2,1)
cat("MAPE for the best model ARIMA(0,2,1):", mape_arima021, "%\n")
## MAPE for the best model ARIMA(0,2,1): 2.218391 %
# Calculate MAPE for the good model ARIMA(0,2,3)
mape_arima023 <- mean(abs(colorado_cases[346:386,'CO']$CO - all_forecasts[,'ARIMA(0,2,3)']) / colorado_cases[346:386,'CO']$CO) * 100

# Print MAPE for the good model ARIMA(0,2,3)
cat("MAPE for the good model ARIMA(0,2,3):", mape_arima023, "%\n")
## MAPE for the good model ARIMA(0,2,3): 2.449765 %
# Calculate MAPE for the combined forecast
mape_combined <- mean(abs(colorado_cases[346:386,'CO']$CO - weighted_average_forecast) / colorado_cases[346:386,'CO']$CO) * 100

# Print MAPE for the combined forecast
cat("MAPE for the combined forecast:", mape_combined, "%\n")
